Police officers at the  Kyumbi police station in Athi River held prayers to cleanse the station as they mourned their departed colleagues. Several pastors, community leaders, and members of the public joined the officers at the station on Tuesday afternoon. Kyumbi Pastors Association chairman Reverend Daniel Muthoka said they will continue praying for the officers to ensure no more deaths occur at the station. While Francis Wambua Kavyu called on the Kenya National Highway Authority (KeNHA) to erect bumps next to Chumbi shopping centre which will slow down speeding vehicles. They expressed their grief as they mourned Corporal Purity Kungu and Corporal Loise Chepchumba who were both attached to Kyumbi police post until their demise. According to Athi River sub-county police commander Anderson Njagi,  the police station had lost two police officers to road accidents in a span of less than a week. Both officers hail from Nakuru County. Corporal Kungu was critically injured on September 22nd night after being knocked down by a vehicle while crossing the busy Nairobi – Mombasa highway at Kyumbi area, according to Athi River sub-county police commander Anderson Njagi. She died the next day at Machakos Level 5 Hospital. Corporal Chepchumba on the other hand,  was knocked down while responding to an accident scene on the same road in the same area on Sunday at around midnight. She died on the spot. The matter was reported to Kyumbi Police Station under Fatal road traffic accident involving a police officer on OB Number 3/26/9/2021 at 12.50 am. “Two officers were attending a scene, placing reflectors on the road when another vehicle came and knocked down the female officer,” Njagi said.  Video Of The Day: Former sports CS Hassan Wario convicted over Rio games scam